<subsection xml:id="subsec-determining-the-position-of-items-in-a-matrix-in-different-situations">
    <title>Determining the Position of Items in a Matrix in Different Situations</title>
    <p>
        Every number or item in a matrix has a special place, just like a seat in a classroom or a product on a shelf. We use the row and column numbers to find the exact position of each item. This helps us quickly locate information in tables, scoreboards, or lists.
    </p>
    <activity>
        
        <p></p>
        <p>Imagine a 3Ã—3 grid representing a simple map. Each cell can have a value: 0 (empty), 1 (tree), 2 (house), 3 (treasure). The map is represented by the following matrix:</p>
        <p>
            <m>
            M = \begin{bmatrix}
            0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
            2 &amp; 3 &amp; 1 \\
            0 &amp; 2 &amp; 0 \\
            \end{bmatrix}
            </m>
        </p>
        <p><m>Map Matrix Adventure (Work in Groups)</m>What you need:  </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Notebook</li>
                <li>Pen or pencil</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p><m>\textbf{Instructions:}</m></p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li><m>\textbf{Explore the map:}</m>  
                    <ul>
                        <li>What is at position (2,2)? What does it represent?</li>
                        <li>List all the positions where there is a house.</li>
                        <li>If you start at (1,1) and move to (2,2), what do you find?</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><m>\textbf{Draw:}</m>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Draw a simple sketch of the map using the matrix values as symbols (0=empty, 1=tree, 2=house, 3=treasure).</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><m>\textbf{Discuss:}</m> 
                    <ul>
                        <li>How does knowing the position (row, column) help you find information quickly?</li>
                        <li>Can you think of another example (like a seating chart or timetable) where positions in a matrix are useful?</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><m>\textbf{Reflect and Share:}</m> 
                    <ul>
                        <li>Share your map and answers with another group. Did you find the same locations for the houses and treasure?</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p><m>\textbf{Key Takeaway: }</m></p>
    <p> The position (row, column) helps us locate and understand data 
        in real-life matrices, maps, and grids. It makes finding information
         quick and fun!
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>What is at position (2,2) in the matrix below?</p>
        <p>List all positions where there is a house (2).</p>
        <p>If you start at (1,1) and move to (2,2), what do you find?</p>
        <p>
            <m>
            M = \begin{bmatrix}
                0 &amp; 1 &amp; 0 \\
                2 &amp; 3 &amp; 1 \\
                0 &amp; 2 &amp; 0 \\
            \end{bmatrix}
            </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Step 1: Look up the value at (2,2):</p>
            <p>The value is 3 (<m>\textbf{treasure}</m>).</p>
            <p>Step 2: Find all positions with value 2 (house):</p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>(2,1)</li>
                    <li>(3,2)</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>Step 3: Moving from (1,1) to (2,2) leads to the treasure.</p>
            <p>Step 4: Students draw a grid and fill in the symbols for each value.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>
</subsection>